## File 1 — web/app.py (Flask Application)

```python
from flask import Flask
import os

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return '''
    <h1>🐳 Docker Compose Lab</h1>
    <p>Flask is running as user: <strong>{}</strong></p>
    <p>Container hostname: <strong>{}</strong></p>
    <p>Traffic came through Nginx reverse proxy!</p>
    '''.format(os.popen('whoami').read().strip(),
               os.popen('hostname').read().strip())

@app.route('/health')
def health():
    return {'status': 'healthy', 'service': 'flask'}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
```

**What each part does:**

| Part | Explanation |
|---|---|
| `from flask import Flask` | Import Flask framework |
| `@app.route('/')` | Handle requests to the root URL |
| `os.popen('whoami')` | Run whoami command — proves non-root user |
| `os.popen('hostname')` | Shows container ID as hostname |
| `@app.route('/health')` | Health check endpoint — returns JSON |
| `host='0.0.0.0'` | Listen on ALL interfaces inside container |
| `port=5000` | Flask runs on port 5000 internally |

**Why `host='0.0.0.0'`?**
```
Without it → Flask only listens on 127.0.0.1 (localhost inside container)
             Nginx cannot reach it from outside the container
             Everything breaks

With it    → Flask listens on ALL interfaces
             Nginx can reach Flask across the Docker network
             Traffic flows correctly
```

