## File 2 — web/requirements.txt

```
flask==3.0.0
```

**Why pin the version?**
```
flask          → installs whatever is latest TODAY
                 next month latest might be different
                 could break your app

flask==3.0.0   → always installs exactly 3.0.0
                 same version every time
                 consistent across all environments
                 this is production best practice
```

---

## File 3 — web/Dockerfile (Multi-stage + Non-root)

```dockerfile
# ── Stage 1: Builder ──────────────────────────
FROM python:3.11 AS builder

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --user --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

# ── Stage 2: Production (slim + non-root) ─────
FROM python:3.11-slim AS production

RUN groupadd -r appuser && useradd -r -g appuser appuser

WORKDIR /app

COPY --from=builder /root/.local /home/appuser/.local
COPY --from=builder /app .

RUN chown -R appuser:appuser /app

USER appuser

EXPOSE 5000

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
```

### Stage 1 — Builder (Line by Line)

**`FROM python:3.11 AS builder`**
```
Start from the full Python 3.11 image (about 900MB)
"AS builder" gives this stage a name
We use this name later to copy files FROM it
This image has compilers, pip, everything needed to BUILD
```

**`WORKDIR /app`**
```
Create /app directory inside the container
AND automatically cd into it
All commands after this run from /app
Same as: mkdir /app && cd /app
```

**`COPY requirements.txt .`**
```
Copy requirements.txt from your machine into /app
The dot (.) = current directory = /app
We copy this BEFORE app code — this is intentional
See "Layer Caching" explanation below
```

**`RUN pip install --user --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt`**
```
Install Flask and all dependencies
--user           → install into /root/.local (not system-wide)
                   important! We copy just this folder to Stage 2
                   instead of the entire Python installation
--no-cache-dir   → don't save pip download cache
                   reduces image size
-r               → read from requirements file
```

**`COPY . .`**
```
Copy ALL your app files into /app
First dot  → everything on YOUR machine (current directory)
Second dot → into /app inside the container
This runs AFTER pip install — layer caching optimization
```

### Why Two Stages? (The Key Concept)

```
Stage 1 (builder)               Stage 2 (production)
─────────────────               ────────────────────
python:3.11 = 900MB        →    python:3.11-slim = 60MB
pip, compilers, gcc        →    none of these needed
build tools                →    not needed to RUN the app
installed packages         →    COPY just the packages ✓
app code                   →    COPY just the code ✓

Final result: 80MB image instead of 900MB
Smaller = faster to pull, less attack surface, cheaper storage
```

### Stage 2 — Production (Line by Line)

**`FROM python:3.11-slim AS production`**
```
Start completely FRESH from a slim Python image
Slim = no compilers, no pip extras, minimal OS
About 60MB vs 900MB for full image
This is the image that actually goes to production
```

**`RUN groupadd -r appuser && useradd -r -g appuser appuser`**
```
groupadd -r appuser    → create a system group named appuser
                         -r means system group (no login shell)

useradd -r             → create a system user
        -g appuser     → put them in the appuser group
        appuser        → name the user appuser

Why not root?
→ If container is compromised and running as root
  attacker gets ROOT on the host machine
→ If running as appuser
  attacker gets a limited unprivileged user
  cannot install packages, cannot modify system files
  massive security improvement
```

**`COPY --from=builder /root/.local /home/appuser/.local`**
```
This is the magic of multi-stage builds

--from=builder        → reach back into Stage 1
/root/.local          → where pip --user installed Flask in Stage 1
/home/appuser/.local  → copy it into appuser's home in Stage 2

We carry ONLY the installed packages
Not the entire 900MB build environment
Just the 20MB of Flask and its dependencies
```

**`COPY --from=builder /app .`**
```
Grab our app code (app.py, requirements.txt) from Stage 1
Copy into current WORKDIR (/app) in Stage 2
Again using --from=builder to reference Stage 1
```

**`RUN chown -R appuser:appuser /app`**
```
chown = change ownership
-R    = recursive (applies to ALL files and folders inside /app)
appuser:appuser = user:group

Why needed?
→ All the files were COPY'd in while running as root
→ appuser doesn't own them yet
→ Without this, appuser cannot read or execute the files
→ This gives appuser full ownership of /app
```

**`USER appuser`**
```
Switch from root to appuser
Every command after this runs as appuser
The Flask app itself runs as appuser
This is the security line — everything after is non-root

Verify it works:
docker compose exec web whoami
→ returns: appuser (NOT root)
```

**`EXPOSE 5000`**
```
Documentation — tells Docker and developers this app uses port 5000
Does NOT actually open or publish the port
Actual port mapping happens in docker-compose.yml or docker run
Think of it as a comment for humans reading the Dockerfile
```

**`CMD ["python", "app.py"]`**
```
Default command when container starts
Runs: python app.py

Why array format ["python", "app.py"] not string "python app.py"?
→ Array = exec form, runs directly, no shell
→ String = shell form, spawns /bin/sh first
→ Array is safer, signals (like SIGTERM) go directly to Python
→ Graceful shutdown works correctly with array form
```

### Layer Caching — Why Order Matters

```dockerfile
# WRONG ORDER — slow builds
COPY . .                    # copies app code
RUN pip install ...         # installs dependencies
# Problem: every time you change app.py
# Docker re-runs pip install (slow, 2-3 minutes)

# CORRECT ORDER — fast builds  
COPY requirements.txt .     # copy deps file first
RUN pip install ...         # install (cached if requirements unchanged)
COPY . .                    # copy app code last
# Now: changing app.py only invalidates the last COPY
# pip install uses cache = 5 second builds
```

---

## File 4 — nginx/nginx.conf

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://web:5000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    }

    location /health {
        proxy_pass http://web:5000/health;
    }
}
```

**Line by line:**

**`listen 80`**
```
Nginx listens for incoming connections on port 80
This is the standard HTTP port
Users hit localhost:80 and Nginx receives it here
```

**`location / { ... }`**
```
Match ALL requests (anything starting with /)
Every URL goes through this block
/ matches everything: /, /about, /api/users, etc.
```

**`proxy_pass http://web:5000`**
```
Forward the request to Flask

web   → the SERVICE NAME defined in docker-compose.yml
        Docker DNS resolves "web" to Flask container's IP
        automatically — same custom network magic
        you don't need to know the IP address

5000  → Flask's port inside the container

This is why Flask doesn't need exposed ports in compose
It's only reachable internally through Nginx
```

**`proxy_set_header Host $host`**
```
Pass the original Host header to Flask
Without this → Flask sees Host: web:5000 (internal)
With this    → Flask sees Host: localhost (what user typed)
Important for apps that check the Host header
```

**`proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr`**
```
Pass the real client IP address to Flask
Without this → Flask thinks every request comes from Nginx
               logs show 172.20.0.3 for everything
With this    → Flask gets the actual client IP
               important for logging, rate limiting, security
```

**Why Nginx in front of Flask?**
```
Flask alone:
→ Single threaded by default
→ Not designed for high traffic
→ No SSL termination built in
→ No rate limiting
→ No static file caching
→ Exposed directly to internet = security risk

Nginx + Flask:
→ Nginx handles thousands of concurrent connections
→ Nginx terminates SSL (HTTPS)
→ Nginx rate limits bad actors
→ Nginx serves static files itself (fast)
→ Flask only handles actual app logic
→ Flask never faces the internet directly
```

---

## File 5 — nginx/Dockerfile

```dockerfile
FROM nginx:alpine

RUN rm /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/app.conf

EXPOSE 80

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
```

**Line by line:**

**`FROM nginx:alpine`**
```
Alpine = tiny Linux distro (5MB vs 200MB for Ubuntu)
nginx:alpine = about 25MB total
vs nginx:latest = about 140MB
Always use alpine for production when possible
Same functionality, fraction of the size
```

**`RUN rm /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf`**
```
Remove nginx's default configuration
Default config serves static HTML files
We don't want that — we want our reverse proxy config
Must remove it first or both configs conflict
```

**`COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/app.conf`**
```
Copy OUR nginx.conf into the container
Place it in /etc/nginx/conf.d/ where nginx reads configs
Named app.conf (can be any name ending in .conf)
This replaces the default behavior with our reverse proxy
```

**`CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]`**
```
Start nginx in the foreground

daemon off = do NOT run as a background daemon
Why? Docker containers need a foreground process
     If nginx daemonizes (goes to background)
     The container thinks nothing is running
     Container immediately exits
daemon off keeps nginx in foreground
Container stays alive as long as nginx runs
```

---

## File 6 — docker-compose.yml

```yaml
version: '3.8'

services:

  web:
    build:
      context: ./web
      dockerfile: Dockerfile
    networks:
      - app-network
    restart: always
    environment:
      - FLASK_ENV=production

  nginx:
    build:
      context: ./nginx
      dockerfile: Dockerfile
    container_name: nginx-proxy
    ports:
      - "80:80"
    networks:
      - app-network
    depends_on:
      - web
    restart: always

networks:
  app-network:
    driver: bridge
```

**Line by line:**

**`services:`**
```
Defines all containers in your stack
Each item under services = one container
```

**`web:` and `nginx:`**
```
Service names — you choose these
They become the DNS names on the network
Nginx finds Flask by typing http://web:5000
because the service is named "web"
```

**`build: context: ./web`**
```
Build an image from a Dockerfile
context: ./web → look in the web/ folder
dockerfile: Dockerfile → use the file named Dockerfile
Docker sends everything in ./web to the build engine
```

**`networks: - app-network`**
```
Connect this container to app-network
Both web and nginx are on the same network
This enables container-to-container DNS
web can ping nginx, nginx can reach web
```

**`restart: always`**
```
If container crashes → restart it automatically
If Docker daemon restarts → start containers automatically
If your EC2 reboots → containers come back up
Production requirement — you can't babysit containers
```

**`environment: - FLASK_ENV=production`**
```
Set environment variables inside the container
FLASK_ENV=production → tells Flask to run in production mode
                        disables debug mode
                        more secure, better performance
```

**`ports: - "80:80"`**
```
Map host port → container port
"80:80" = your machine port 80 → nginx container port 80

Only nginx has ports exposed
Flask (web) has NO ports section
Flask is internal only — unreachable from outside
Only Nginx can talk to Flask
This is correct production security pattern
```

**`depends_on: - web`**
```
Start web container BEFORE nginx starts
Without this → nginx might start before Flask is ready
               nginx tries to connect, Flask not ready yet
               nginx crashes on startup
depends_on ensures correct startup order
```

**`networks: app-network: driver: bridge`**
```
Define the custom network explicitly
driver: bridge = standard Docker bridge network
                 containers get their own IPs
                 DNS resolution by service name
                 isolated from other Docker networks

Without this section → Compose creates a default network
                        still works but not explicitly defined
With this section    → you control the network configuration
                        can add subnet, IP ranges, etc.
```

---

## Every Docker Compose Command Used

### Starting & Building

**`docker compose up -d --build`**
```
The most important command — used every single deployment

up       → create and start all containers
-d       → detached mode (runs in background)
--build  → rebuild images before starting
           even if image already exists

When to use:
→ First time running the project
→ After changing any Dockerfile
→ After changing app code
→ Any deployment to production

What it does step by step:
1. Reads docker-compose.yml
2. Builds all images with build: sections
3. Creates the custom network (app-network)
4. Starts containers in dependency order
5. Returns control to your terminal
```

**`docker compose build`**
```
Rebuild images WITHOUT starting containers
Useful when you want to build first, start later
docker compose build web → rebuild just the web service
```

**`docker compose pull`**
```
Pull latest versions of images from Docker Hub
Useful before deploying to get security patches
docker compose pull → pulls nginx:alpine, postgres:15 etc
```

### Checking Status

**`docker compose ps`**
```
Show status of all services in this compose project

Output columns:
NAME     → container name
IMAGE    → which image it's using
COMMAND  → what command is running inside
SERVICE  → which service from compose file
STATUS   → Up/Exited/Restarting
PORTS    → port mappings (host:container)
```

**`docker compose logs`**
```
Show logs from ALL services combined
Color coded by service name
flask-app logs in one color, nginx-proxy in another
```

**`docker compose logs -f`**
```
Follow logs live (like tail -f)
-f = follow, streams new log lines as they appear
Ctrl+C to stop following
```

**`docker compose logs -f web`**
```
Follow logs for just ONE service
Replace "web" with any service name
Useful when debugging a specific container
```

### Getting Inside Containers

**`docker compose exec web bash`**
```
Open a bash shell inside the running web container
exec  → execute a command in running container
web   → the service name
bash  → the command to run

You land inside the container as the running user
In our case: appuser (NOT root)
Your prompt changes to: appuser@<container-id>:/app$
```

**`docker compose exec web whoami`**
```
Run a single command inside the container
whoami → prints current user
Returns: appuser (proves non-root is working)
```

**`docker compose exec db psql -U postgres`**
```
Get into postgres database directly
db    → the database service name
psql  → postgres command line client
-U postgres → connect as postgres user
```

**`docker compose run web python migrate.py`**
```
Run a ONE-OFF command in a NEW container
Different from exec (which uses existing running container)
Use case: database migrations before starting the app
          running tests
          one-time setup scripts
Container is created, runs the command, then removed
```

### Managing Services

**`docker compose restart`**
```
Restart ALL services
Stops and starts all containers
```

**`docker compose restart nginx`**
```
Restart just ONE service
Other services keep running uninterrupted
Use case: you changed nginx.conf and need nginx to reload
```

**`docker compose up -d --scale web=2`**
```
Run MULTIPLE instances of a service

--scale web=2 → run 2 copies of the web service
web           → the service name from compose file
2             → how many instances

Docker auto-names them:
compose-lab-web-1
compose-lab-web-2

IMPORTANT: Cannot use container_name with scaling
container_name forces ONE specific name
scaling needs unique names for each instance
Remove container_name from the service to enable scaling

Nginx automatically load balances between instances
```

### Stopping & Cleanup

**`docker compose down`**
```
Stop and REMOVE all containers and networks
Images are kept (you can restart quickly)
Volumes are kept (data is safe)

What gets removed:
→ All containers
→ The custom network (app-network)

What stays:
→ Images (compose-lab-web, compose-lab-nginx)
→ Volumes (any named volumes)
→ Your code files
```

**`docker compose down -v`**
```
Stop, remove containers, networks AND volumes
-v = also delete named volumes

USE WITH CAUTION in production
This deletes your database data if using volumes
Use case: completely reset the environment
          start fresh including database
```

**`docker compose down --rmi all`**
```
Nuclear option — removes everything

Removes:
→ All containers
→ All networks
→ All images built by this compose file

After this: docker images | grep compose-lab → nothing

Use case: completely clean up a project
          free up disk space
          start totally fresh
```

